summary:
The Security Council:

Recalling previous relevant resolutions, including 825 (1993), 1540 (2004), 1695 (2006), 1718 (2006), 1874 (2009), and 1887 (2009),

 Condemns the DPRKâ€™s 12 December 2012 launch, which used ballistic missile technology and violated resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009);

Demands the DPRK not proceed with further launches using ballistic missile technology, comply with resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009), and re-establish its pre-existing commitments to a moratorium on missile launches;

Demands the DPRK immediately comply with its obligations under resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009), including abandoning all nuclear weapons and existing nuclear programs in a complete, verifiable, and irreversible manner;

Reaffirms current sanctions measures contained in resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009);

Imposes measures specified in paragraph 8 of resolution 1718 (2006) on individuals and entities listed in Annex I and II;

Calls upon Member States to exercise enhanced vigilance, including monitoring activities of their nationals, financial institutions, and entities;

Directs the Committee to issue an Implementation Assistance Notice regarding situations where a vessel has refused to allow an inspection;

Recalls that States may seize and dispose of items consistent with the provisions of resolutions 1718 (2006), 1874 (2009), and this resolution;

Clarifies that measures imposed in resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009) prohibit the transfer of items if a State has information that provides reasonable grounds to believe that a designated individual or entity is involved;

Calls upon Member States to report on measures taken to implement provisions of resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009);

Encourages international agencies to ensure their activities with respect to the DPRK are consistent with the provisions of resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009);

Deplores violations of measures imposed in resolutions 1718 (2006) and 1874 (2009), including the use of bulk cash to evade sanctions, and calls on States to exercise vigilance and restraint regarding the entry into or transit through their territories of individuals working on behalf or at the direction of a designated individual or entity.
